, 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomasson, K." box="[426,619,2030,2056]" pageId="10" pageNumber="238" pagination="1 - 57" refId="ref9701" refString="Thomasson, K. (1971) Amazonian desmids. Memoires Institute Royal des Sciences Naturelles de Belgique 86: 1 - 57." type="journal article" year="1971">Thomasson 1971</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Bittencourt-Oliveira, M. C." box="[629,921,2030,2056]" pageId="10" pageNumber="238" pagination="477 - 488" refId="ref7139" refString="Bittencourt-Oliveira, M. C. (1993) Ficoflorula do Reservatorio de Balbina, estado do Amazonas, III: Classe Zygnemaphyceae. Revista Brasileira de Biologia 53 (3): 477 - 488." type="journal article" year="1993">Bittencourt-Oliveira 1993</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Lopes, M. R. M. &amp; Bicudo, C. E. M." box="[930,1177,2030,2057]" pageId="10" pageNumber="238" pagination="167 - 212" refId="ref8385" refString="Lopes, M. R. M. &amp; Bicudo, C. E. M. (2003) Desmidioflorula de um lago da planicie de inundacao do Rio Acre, Estado do Amazonas, Brasil. Acta Amazonica 33 (2): 167 - 212. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / 1809 - 4392200332212" type="journal article" year="2003">Lopes &amp; Bicudo 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Souza, K. F. &amp; Melo, S." box="[1187,1412,2030,2056]" pageId="10" pageNumber="238" pagination="335 - 346" refId="ref9547" refString="Souza, K. F. &amp; Melo, S. (2011) Desmids (Chlorophyta) from lake Novo (Amapa, Brazil): genera Staurastrum, Staurodesmus e Xanthidium. Acta Amazonica 41 (3): 335 - 346. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0044 - 59672011000300002" type="journal article" year="2011">Souza &amp; Melo 2011</bibRefCitation>
), in which morphological variation can be seen on the margins between the basal and polar lobes, right to rounded angles; apical margin, retuse to rounded; protrusion on the face of the semicell from shallow to projected, and ornamented by obtuse granules or granules with spiniform ends.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[136,1452,158,832]" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">
Some specimens identified in the present study are similar to those illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomasson, K." box="[1085,1288,230,256]" pageId="11" pageNumber="239" pagination="1 - 57" refId="ref9701" refString="Thomasson, K. (1971) Amazonian desmids. Memoires Institute Royal des Sciences Naturelles de Belgique 86: 1 - 57." type="journal article" year="1971">Thomasson (1971</bibRefCitation>
, Pl. 16, fig.14) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Gronblad, R." box="[183,364,266,293]" pageId="11" pageNumber="239" pagination="1 - 44" refId="ref8222" refString="Gronblad, R. (1945) De algis brasiliensibus. Praecipue desmidiaceis in regione inferiore fluminis Amazonas a professore August Ginzberger (Wien) anno MCMXXVII collectis. Acta Societatis Scienctiarum Fennicae 2 (6): 1 - 44." type="journal article" year="1945">Grönblad (1945</bibRefCitation>
, Pl. 8, fig. 148) from specimens collected in the Amazon region.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[136,1452,158,832]" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">
Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nordstedt" authorityYear="1870" box="[389,621,302,328]" class="Conjugatophyceae" family="Desmidiaceae" genus="Xanthidium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygnematales" pageId="11" pageNumber="239" phylum="Charophyta" rank="species" species="trilobum">
<emphasis box="[389,621,302,328]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">Xanthidium trilobum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="West &amp; G. S. West (1897: 88)" authorityName="West &amp; G. S. West" authorityPageNumber="88" authorityYear="1897" box="[745,1234,302,329]" class="Conjugatophyceae" family="Desmidiaceae" genus="Xanthidium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygnematales" pageId="11" pageNumber="239" phylum="Charophyta" rank="species" species="subtrilobum">
<emphasis box="[745,910,302,328]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">X. subtrilobum</emphasis>
West &amp; G.S. 
<bibRefCitation author="West, W. &amp; West, G. S." box="[1047,1234,302,328]" pageId="11" pageNumber="239" pagination="297 - 304" refId="ref9770" refString="West, W. &amp; West, G. S. (1897) Welwitsch's African freshwater algae. Journal of Botany, British and Foreign 35: 1 - 7, 33 - 42, 77 - 89, 113 - 122, 172 - 183, 235 - 243, 264 - 272, 297 - 304." type="journal article" year="1897">West (1897: 88)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, especially because of the shape of the cell, although the latter differs by having semicells with a spine not forked at the angles of the lobes, and the presence of a spine in the middle of the outer margin of each lateral lobe in apical view.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[136,1452,158,832]" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">
The zygospore with long, apically furcated spines analyzed in the Marimbus do Baiano were similar to reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Coesel, P. F. M." box="[174,335,446,472]" pageId="11" pageNumber="239" pagination="109 - 119" refId="ref7402" refString="Coesel, P. F. M. (1988) Desmid zygospores from French Guiana and the phenomenon of simultaneous conjugation in multi-species assemblies. Cryptogamie, Algologie 19 (1 - 2): 109 - 119." type="journal article" year="1988">Coesel (1988)</bibRefCitation>
for the material collected in a shallow pool in Eskol, municipality of Roura, south of Cayenne, 
<collectingCountry box="[136,306,482,508]" name="French Guiana" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[136,1452,158,832]" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">
The 
<collectionCode box="[240,298,518,544]" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">SEM</collectionCode>
images of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nordstedt" authorityYear="1870" box="[421,549,518,544]" class="Conjugatophyceae" family="Desmidiaceae" genus="Xanthidium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygnematales" pageId="11" pageNumber="239" phylum="Charophyta" rank="species" species="trilobum">
<emphasis box="[421,549,518,544]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">X. trilobum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cells observed (
<figureCitation box="[731,812,518,545]" captionStart="FIGURES 66–67" captionStartId="7.[136,243,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[193,1394,198,1922]" captionTargetId="figure-28@7.[185,1402,190,1929]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 66–67. Xanthidium nordstedtii (66): frontal view (SEM). Xanthidium trilobum (67): frontal view (SEM). Scale Bar: 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6331888" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6331888/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">Fig. 67</figureCitation>
) resembles to material studied to the 
<collectingCountry box="[1231,1342,518,544]" name="Argentina" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">Argentina</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Coute, A. &amp; Tell, G." pageId="11" pageNumber="239" pagination="1 - 228" refId="ref7655" refString="Coute, A. &amp; Tell, G. (1981) Ultrastructure de la paroi cellulaire des desmidiacees au microscope electronique a balaiage. Beih. Nova Hedwigia 68: 1 - 228." type="journal article" year="1981">Couté &amp; Tell (1981: 214</bibRefCitation>
, Pl.10, fig. 3), showing the facial semicells ornamented by a circle of nine granules surrounding a central one, and semicells with projected angles in short cylindrical processes, with 2 spines at the end.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[136,1452,158,832]" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">
<bibRefCitation author="Coesel, P. F. M." box="[189,347,626,653]" pageId="11" pageNumber="239" pagination="41 - 53" refId="ref7364" refString="Coesel, P. F. M. (1996) Biogeography of desmids. Hydrobiologia 336 (1 - 3): 41 - 53. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / BF 00010818" type="journal article" year="1996">Coesel (1996)</bibRefCitation>
, analyzing the biogeography of desmids, commented the possibility that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nordstedt" authorityYear="1870" box="[1145,1376,626,652]" class="Conjugatophyceae" family="Desmidiaceae" genus="Xanthidium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygnematales" pageId="11" pageNumber="239" phylum="Charophyta" rank="species" species="trilobum">
<emphasis box="[1145,1376,626,652]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">Xanthidium trilobum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="West &amp; G. S. West" authorityYear="1897" class="Conjugatophyceae" family="Desmidiaceae" genus="Xanthidium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygnematales" pageId="11" pageNumber="239" phylum="Charophyta" rank="species" species="subtrilobum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">X. subtrilobum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been sister taxa, the former reported from South and Central America, whereas the latter known from Africa, 
<collectionCode box="[223,240,698,724]" country="Sweden" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15668" name="Department of Botany, Swedish Museum of Natural History" pageId="11" pageNumber="239" type="Herbarium">S</collectionCode>
. 
<collectionCode box="[243,265,698,724]" country="United Kingdom" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15670" name="Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh" pageId="11" pageNumber="239" type="Herbarium">E</collectionCode>
. Asia, and 
<collectionCode box="[391,414,699,725]" country="China" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:13092" name="Nanjing University" pageId="11" pageNumber="239" type="Herbarium">N</collectionCode>
. 
<collectingCountry box="[425,531,698,724]" name="Australia" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">Australia</collectingCountry>
; and that the differences in morphology between both taxa occurred by supposed allopatric speciation by the dispersal model (colonization) rather than by the vicariance model (fragmentation).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[136,1452,158,832]" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nordstedt" authorityYear="1870" box="[189,428,770,796]" class="Conjugatophyceae" family="Desmidiaceae" genus="Xanthidium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygnematales" pageId="11" pageNumber="239" phylum="Charophyta" rank="species" species="trilobum">
<emphasis box="[189,428,770,796]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="239">Xanthidium trilobum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was the second most common taxon of the genus in the study area and registered in approximately 37% of all analyzed samples.
</paragraph>
